{"title_page": "Setting (narrative)", "text_new": "The '''setting''' is both the [[time]] and [[location (geographygeographic location]] within a [[narrative]], either [[non-fiction|nonfiction]] or [[fiction]]. A [[literary element]], the setting helps initiate the main [[Theatrical scenery|backdrop]] and [[Mood (literature)|mood]] for a story. Setting has been referred to as story world<ref>{{harvtxt|Truby|2007|p=145}}</ref> or ''[[Social environment|milieu]]'' to include a [[Context (language use)|context]] (especially [[society]]) beyond the immediate surroundings of the story. Elements of setting may include [[culture]], [[historical period]], [[geography]], and [[hour]]. Along with the [[Plot (narrative)|plot]], [[Character (arts)|character]], [[Theme (literature)|theme]], and [[Style (fiction)|style]], setting is considered one of the fundamental components of [[fiction]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Obstfeld|2002|pp=1,65,115,171}}</ref>\n\n==Role==\nSetting is an important element in a narrative. The term setting is often used to refer to the social milieu in which the events of a novel occur<ref>{{harvtxt|Lodge|1992|pp=58\u201360}}</ref> and [[novelist]] [[Donna Levin]] has described how this social milieu shapes the characters\u2019 values.<ref>{{harvtxt|Levin|1992|pp=110\u2013112}}</ref> The elements of the story setting include the passage of time, which may be static in some stories or dynamic in others with, for example, changing seasons. \n\nA setting can exist in three basic forms. One is the natural world, or in an \"outdoor\" place. In this setting, the natural landscapes of the world play an important part in a narrative, along with living creatures and different times of weather conditions and seasons. The second form exists as the cultural and historical background in which the narrative resides. Past events that have impacted the cultural background of characters or locations are significant in this way. The third form of a setting is a public or private place that has been created/maintained and/or resided in by people. Examples of this include a house, a park, a street, a school, etc.<ref>{{harvtxt|Roberts|Zweig|2014|pp=238\u2013239}}</ref>\n\n==Types==\nSetting may take various forms:\n* [[Alternate history (fiction)|Alternate history]]\n* [[Campaign setting]]\n* [[Constructed world]]\n* [[Dystopia]]\n* [[Fantasy world]]\n* [[Fictional city]]\n* [[Fictional country]]\n* [[Fictional crossover]]\n* [[Fictional location]]\n* [[Fictional universe]]\n* [[Future history]]\n* [[Imaginary world]]\n* [[Mythical place]]\n* [[Parallel universe (fiction)|Parallel universe]]\n* [[Planets in science fiction]]\n* [[Simulated reality]]\n* [[Virtual reality]]\n* [[Utopia]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[British regional literature]]\n* [[Index of fictional places]]\n* [[Landscape]]\n* [[List of fictional universes]]\n* [[Setting (disambiguation)|Setting]]\n* [[Worldbuilding]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{citation\n| title = Get That Novel Started\n| first = Donna\n| last = Levin\n| publisher = Writer's Digest Books\n| location = Cincinnati, OH\n| year = 1992\n| isbn = 0-89879-517-6\n| url-access = registration\n| url = https://archive.org/details/getthatnovelstar00levi\n}}\n* {{citation\n| title = The Art of Fiction\n| first = David \n| last= Lodge\n| publisher = Martin, Secker & Warburg Ltd\n| location = London \n| year = 1992\n| isbn = 0-14-017492-3\n}}\n* {{citation\n| title = Fiction First Aid: Instant Remedies for Novels, Stories and Scripts\n| first = Raymond\n| last = Obstfeld\n| publisher = Writer's Digest Books\n| location = Cincinnati, OH\n| year = 2002\n| isbn = 1-58297-117-X\n| url-access = registration\n| url = https://archive.org/details/fictionfirstaidi0000obst\n}}\n* {{citation|title=Literature: An Introduction to Reading and Writing|last=Roberts|first=Edgar V.|last2=Zweig|first2=Robert|publisher=Pearson|year=2014|isbn=9780321944788}}\n* {{cite book\n|title = Write Great Fiction: Description & Setting\n|first = Ron\n|last = Rozelle\n|publisher = Writer's Digest Books\n|location = Cincinnati, OH\n|year = 2005\n|isbn = 1-58297-327-X\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last = Truby\n|first = John\n|title = Anatomy of a Story: 22 Steps to Becoming a Master Storyteller\n|publisher = Faber and Faber, Inc\n|location = New York, NY\n|year = 2007\n|isbn = 978-0-86547-951-7\n}}\n\n{{Fiction writing}}\n\n[[Category:Setting| ]]\n[[Category:Fiction]]\n[[Category:Narratology]]\n", "text_old": "The '''setting''' is both the [[time]] and [[location (geography)|geographic location]] within a [[narrative]], either [[non-fiction|nonfiction]] or [[fiction]]. A [[literary element]], the setting helps initiate the main [[Theatrical scenery|backdrop]] and [[Mood (literature)|mood]] for a story. Setting has been referred to as story world<ref>{{harvtxt|Truby|2007|p=145}}</ref> or ''[[Social environment|milieu]]'' to include a [[Context (language use)|context]] (especially [[society]]) beyond the immediate surroundings of the story. Elements of setting may include [[culture]], [[historical period]], [[geography]], and [[hour]]. Along with the [[Plot (narrative)|plot]], [[Character (arts)|character]], [[Theme (literature)|theme]], and [[Style (fiction)|style]], setting is considered one of the fundamental components of [[fiction]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Obstfeld|2002|pp=1,65,115,171}}</ref>\n\n==Role==\nSetting is an important element in a narrative. The term setting is often used to refer to the social milieu in which the events of a novel occur<ref>{{harvtxt|Lodge|1992|pp=58\u201360}}</ref> and [[novelist]] [[Donna Levin]] has described how this social milieu shapes the characters\u2019 values.<ref>{{harvtxt|Levin|1992|pp=110\u2013112}}</ref> The elements of the story setting include the passage of time, which may be static in some stories or dynamic in others with, for example, changing seasons. \n\nA setting can exist in three basic forms. One is the natural world, or in an \"outdoor\" place. In this setting, the natural landscapes of the world play an important part in a narrative, along with living creatures and different times of weather conditions and seasons. The second form exists as the cultural and historical background in which the narrative resides. Past events that have impacted the cultural background of characters or locations are significant in this way. The third form of a setting is a public or private place that has been created/maintained and/or resided in by people. Examples of this include a house, a park, a street, a school, etc.<ref>{{harvtxt|Roberts|Zweig|2014|pp=238\u2013239}}</ref>\n\n==Types==\nSetting may take various forms:\n* [[Alternate history (fiction)|Alternate history]]\n* [[Campaign setting]]\n* [[Constructed world]]\n* [[Dystopia]]\n* [[Fantasy world]]\n* [[Fictional city]]\n* [[Fictional country]]\n* [[Fictional crossover]]\n* [[Fictional location]]\n* [[Fictional universe]]\n* [[Future history]]\n* [[Imaginary world]]\n* [[Mythical place]]\n* [[Parallel universe (fiction)|Parallel universe]]\n* [[Planets in science fiction]]\n* [[Simulated reality]]\n* [[Virtual reality]]\n* [[Utopia]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[British regional literature]]\n* [[Index of fictional places]]\n* [[Landscape]]\n* [[List of fictional universes]]\n* [[Setting (disambiguation)|Setting]]\n* [[Worldbuilding]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{citation\n| title = Get That Novel Started\n| first = Donna\n| last = Levin\n| publisher = Writer's Digest Books\n| location = Cincinnati, OH\n| year = 1992\n| isbn = 0-89879-517-6\n| url-access = registration\n| url = https://archive.org/details/getthatnovelstar00levi\n}}\n* {{citation\n| title = The Art of Fiction\n| first = David \n| last= Lodge\n| publisher = Martin, Secker & Warburg Ltd\n| location = London \n| year = 1992\n| isbn = 0-14-017492-3\n}}\n* {{citation\n| title = Fiction First Aid: Instant Remedies for Novels, Stories and Scripts\n| first = Raymond\n| last = Obstfeld\n| publisher = Writer's Digest 